\v 1 A psalm of David.\f + \fr 24.1: \ft LXX adds τῆς μιᾶς σαββάτων, “of the first of the week.” This is likely an addition reflecting the liturgical use of this psalm in Jewish worship. See Kraus, Psalms 1–59, 312; Goldingay, Psalms, 1:356. Cf. Koch, “Tempeleinlassliturgien und Dekaloge,” 59, who suggests there is no evidence of post-exilic use of this psalm as a liturgy.\f*
\q1 To Yhwh belongs the earth and its fullness,
\q2 the world and those who dwell\f + \fr 24.1: \ft Qal, Part, mp, construct, ישׁב. BHS: LXX has καὶ πάντες οἱ κατοικοῦντες.\f* in it.
\q1
\v 2 For\f + \fr 24.2: \ft BHS: omitted in LXX, Symmachus, and Theodotian. While this may reflect a different manuscript tradition, the logic of the move from v. 1 to v. 2 is not altered by its absence. Therefore, I follow the MT in preserving it.\f* he founded it\f + \fr 24.2: \ft Qal, Per., 3ms, + 3fs suffix, יסד.\f* on the seas,
\q2 And on the rivers he established it.\f + \fr 24.2: \ft Piel, Impf., 3ms, +3fs suffix, כון.\f*
